{{Underlinked|date=April 2014}}
[[File:Paseo Arts District - Oklahoma City, OK USA, PASEO ART SPACE - panoramio.jpg|thumb|A building in the district, 2014]]
The '''Paseo Arts District''', originally referred to as the Spanish Village,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK/1980/05/22&id=Ar01000&sk=1BFB1BEE|title=Weekend Paseo Festival|last=|first=|date=5/22/1980|website=The Daily Oklahoman|archive-url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK%2F1980%2F05%2F22&id=Ar01000&sk=1BFB1BEE|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> was built in 1929 as the first commercial shopping district north of [[Downtown Oklahoma City]] by Oklahoman G.A. Nichols.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Paseo|work=thepaseo.com|url=http://thepaseo.com/aboutus.html|accessdate=9/11/2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806192350/http://www.thepaseo.com/aboutus.html#|archive-date=2011-08-06|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Early business in the area included a swimming pool called the Paseo Plunge,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK/1951/05/30&id=Ar01103&sk=62432EED|title=Swim!|last=|first=|date=5/30/1951|website=The Daily Oklahoman|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> a dry cleaner, drug store,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK/1939/02/20&id=Ar00703&sk=CCBF7BC4|title=Drugstore Thieves Work Under Lights|last=|first=|date=2/20/1939|website=The Daily Oklahoman|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> shoe repair store,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK/1933/03/31&id=Ar00702&sk=0928A1F4|title=Pippin's Paseo Shoe Rebuilders|last=|first=|date=3/31/1933|website=|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> and restaurants. The Spanish Village era is said to have ended in the mid-1950s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK/1983/05/27&id=Ar14500&sk=65DC8D13|title=Paseo wiping out its hippy-era|last=|first=|date=5/27/1983|website=|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref>

Paseo has undergone transformations; currently, the Paseo is enjoying a renaissance since the 1980s. Today, a vibrant group of artists and other interested people are transforming this community through creative thinking and arts activities.

Located along Paseo Drive at roughly N. Walker Ave and NW 28th Street, the faux Spanish village with its stucco buildings and clay tile roofs is the home to many of [[Oklahoma City]]'s Artists.

The Paseo Arts district is home to a number of chic bars, restaurants, boutiques, nightclubs, art galleries, and avant-garde businesses. Since 1975, Paseo hosts the annual Paseo Arts Festival each [[Memorial Day]] weekend, which showcases original works of visual and performing arts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.newsok.com/olive/apa/oklahoman/SharedView.Article.aspx?href=DOK/1984/05/23&id=Ar06900&sk=C9D602AC|title=Paseo Festival's Foothold Solid After Nine Years|last=|first=|date=5/23/1984|website=The Daily Oklahoman|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref>  Other events within the Paseo Arts district include its annual Fairy Ball, as well as the First Friday Gallery Walk. The First Friday Gallery Walk  is an event in which Paseo art galleries and restaurants host Art Opening Receptions on the first Friday of every month in order to displaying new artist's work and invite people to visit the Paseo district.<ref>{{cite web|title=First Friday|work=thepaseo.com/calendar/firstfriday.html|accessdate=9/11/2011}}</ref>

The district is also home to the oldest church in Oklahoma, Old Trinity of Paseo.<ref>http://www.oldtrinityofpaseo.com/</ref> The former Anglican church was built in [[New Brunswick]], [[Canada]] in 1842 and was closed in 1990. Oklahoma City photographer Tom Lee purchased the church in 2000 and had it dismantled and moved to Oklahoma City to serve as his studio. Lee sold the church in 2007 to be rented as a venue for weddings and other events.<ref>http://okc.net/2011/01/31/keeping-okc-weird-a-rough-guide-to-the-paseo/</ref>

The Paseo district is listed as a neighborhood ‘worthy of preservation’<ref>{{cite web|title=National Register of Historic Places|work=nps.gov/nr/}}</ref> on the [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Oklahoma County, Oklahoma|National Register of Historic Places]] and in 2010, was named as one of the ’10 Great Neighborhoods for 2010’ by the American Planning Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=NewsOK Article|work=newsok.com |url=http://newsok.com/okcs-paseo-named-as-one-of-americas-10-great-neighborhoods-for-2010/article/3504008|accessdate=9/11/2011}}</ref>

Among the galleries in the district is JRB Art at the Elms Gallery, housed in the former home of painter and museum director [[Nan Sheets]].<ref name="ionok.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.ionok.com/culture/arts/nan-sheets-artist-scrapbook/|title=Nan Sheets: Artist Scrapbook|publisher=|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>

